{"commentID": 194, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Recently, courts have held that debt collectors can escape 1692i's venue provisions entirely by pursuing debt collection through arbitration instead.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "As the NAF studies reflect, arbitration has not proven a satisfactory alternative.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I urge the CFPB to include in a rule language interpreting 1692i as requiring debt collectors to proceed in court, not through largely-unregulated arbitral forums.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 195, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "State and local court rules sometimes make default judgments much more likely.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "For example, when a person who allegedly owes a debt is told to come to court on a work day, they may be forced to choose between a default judgment and their job.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "I urge the CFPB to find practices that involve scheduling hearings at inconvenient times unfair, deceptive, and abusive, or inconsistent with 1692i.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 196, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "When alleged debtors are served with state court summonses, they are not always comprehensible to laypersons.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Any requirements to file papers to avoid default judgment", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The date of any scheduled hearing and procedures for changing the date", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Local and online sources of information for pro se defendants, and possibly local non-profit advice organizations.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "That the debtor may wish to consider bankruptcy if they cannot pay their debts.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 197, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "There is currently a split between the Ninth and First Circuits as to whether 1692i and other FDCPA provisions apply in garnishment proceedings.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In many states, the nominal defendant is the judgment debtor's employer,", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but the judgment debtor is the real party in interest.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "To allow consumers to better assert the defenses to and exemptions from garnishment available under state law, the CFPB should issue a rule applying 1692i to garnishment proceedings.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 198, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "In many districts where bad check diversion programs exist, there is anecdotal evidence that the companies administering the programs threaten with prosecution individuals who do not come within the state's bad check law", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "for example, checks that bounce due to printing errors, checks for which there were funds available when written but not when presented, and individuals who pay the amount due by other means within grace periods permitted by state law.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The CFPB should ensure that bad check diversion programs have a realistic means of ensuring that only individuals realistically subject to prosecution are targeted,", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and should also require that, in order to qualify for the 1692p safe harbor, diversion programs prohibit misleading communications and misstatements of state bad check law.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 199, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "To avoid consumers getting sued repeatedly on the same debt, the CFPB should require or encourage states to adopt rules requiring that judgments be preclusive of future consumer-collector litigation on the same debt;", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "instead, if there is a dispute between assignees as to who has title to the debt, they should work it out between themselves instead of risking subjecting the consumer to multiple liability.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 200, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Consumer attorneys occasionally advise their clients not to record unlawful communications due to state laws requiring both parties' consent for recording.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The CFPB should require that debt collectors subject to the FDCPA impliedly consent to recording by consumers.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 201, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "When an attorney is a 'Debt Collector' (as per their own documents) and not legally considered a 'Collection Agency' the attorney is not held accountable for consumer protection law violations (both local and federal) within civil court.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This loop hole needs to be addressed.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "The attorneys/debt collectors are not monitored by the state bar", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because it is a collection practice ", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "(the attorneys buy old debt and then collect upon that debt in civil court", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["6"], "text": "and the state and federal civil courts are not monitoring the attorneys", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because it is an attorneys office and not considered a collection agency ", "type": "fact", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "- even though the attorneys buy old debt then take alleged debtors to civil court.", "type": "fact", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["9"], "text": "I personally know of a very large attorney agency in Washington State that even gives classes thru the Washington state bar to other attorneys", "type": "testimony", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because it is a easy caseload to win.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 203, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "There is currently dispute among federal district and circuit courts as to whether a post-default assignee of a debt comes within the creditor exception.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The CFPB should issue a rule providing that a post-default assignee is a collector for FDCPA purposes.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 204, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "The FDCPA contains an exception for creditors.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The CFPB should include in any rule confirmation that the same practices prohibited for collectors under the FDCPA would be unfair, deceptive, or abusive acts and practices if done by a creditor.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 205, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Assignments without notice could lead to consumers paying the wrong person.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The CFPB should encourage proper notice by ruling that a payment made to either of the assignee or the assignor reduces the debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 206, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "The original creditor has information about the debtor's language;", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "ii) The collector obtains information about the debtor's language; *or*", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "iii) The debtor lives in a ZIP code known to have a significant (5%?) number of non-English speakers.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This requirement should only apply to languages with large LEP populations - a threshold might be 100,000 - to avoid undue cost.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "For smaller populations, where obtaining a full translation might be uneconomical, collectors could include the following passage translated into the appropriate languages on an otherwise English letter:", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 207, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I work at a private university", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and we do not sue for collections.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Since the debt can be reported to the credit bureau for 7 years,", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "we like to keep our accounts at collection agencies during that entire time.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "With the language now being offered due to time-barred states, our collection agencies do not want any of our accounts older than 4 years (TX).", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 208, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I received a bill from an attorneys office regarding a bill I did not think that was mine.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I sent a certified return receipt request for validation but never received a response.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "So I sent a 2nd certified return receipt - request for validation and again never received a response.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The attorneys office filed a civil suit and took me to court.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I explained this to the judge and gave proof.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The proof I submitted into the court file were copies of request of validation, the USPS certified letter statement's and request verification receipt statement's.", "type": "testimony", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7"], "text": "This was all ignored by the judge ", "type": "testimony", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because I was pro se and did not know Washington state law.", "type": "testimony", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I had made the request prior to this case being filed.", "type": "testimony", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Later it was explained to me by an attorney that the local county civil courts do not enforce federal laws, only state laws and in state court a request for validation is not recognized.", "type": "testimony", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["11"], "text": "I also requested proof of licensing which I did not receive ", "type": "testimony", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because the plaintiff was and currently is not a licensed in Washington state as a debt collection agency ", "type": "testimony", "id": 11, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "- they are attorneys.", "type": "testimony", "id": 12, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The plaintiff won their case", "type": "testimony", "id": 13, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and I owed a debt that was not mine.", "type": "testimony", "id": 14, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I ask you, where is the fairness in this?", "type": "value", "id": 15, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["15"], "text": "What needs to occur is the laws need to be made clear for both the lay person and the judicial system.", "type": "policy", "id": 16, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 210, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I'm aware of that,", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but I don't think many appellate courts have considered the issue.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "To confirm that it's the law, it should be included in a rule.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 212, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I do NOT owe any debt but have a COMMON FIRST and LAST NAME.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "My Constitutional rights are violated every time a lawyer fails to perform due diligence, per rule 137, BEFORE SIGNING and FILING COURT PAPER against me.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The clerks are helpless, ", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "the judges & attorney disciplinary do nothing favoring \"lawyer zealousness.\"", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I then have to spend time & money, going to court to prove I am NOT the person who owes the debt.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I urge the CFPB to create mechanisms for clerks & citizens that make it 1) easier to fix these messes &, 2) to bring sanctions against lawyers & judges for MISUSE OF LEGAL PROCEDURE, ABUSE OF PROCESS, WRONGFUL CIVIL PROCEEDINGS, & MALICIOUS PROSECUTION.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 217, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1", "2_3"], "text": "Allow the States and/or local courts administer lawsuits.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Regardless of any added rules, documents, etc. none will help increase debtors attending hearings.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Since 1964 I have seen no significant increase of consumers attending hearings.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I have, however, seen the major reason being attributed to not understanding due process by consumers.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
