{"commentID": 228, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "There should be no option to attempt to verify the debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Attempts should always be required", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and if verification is not made, the debt cannot be further transferred.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 230, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1_3"], "text": "FDCPA should define what constitutes reasonable period of time.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In my experience most attorneys who represent a debtor do not return communication inquiries about representation.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In most cases the delay in response may be caused by the debtor paying installment payments to the attorney to file a bankruptcy proceeding.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "When the debtor does not keep the repayment terms a creditor is presently not notified that the representation has terminated ", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and there is no attorney representation.", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 231, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Collectors are responsible for re-establishing contact with delinquent customers and providing services that facilitate repayment of the loans, regardless of the technology utilized.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In Collections, automated dialing systems effectively increase the ability for the collector to reach delinquent customers unwilling to proactively reach out to the creditors.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Automated dialing systems are used in many other ways not related to debt collection: telemarketers use them to reach potential customers, schools use them to notify parents of closings due to inclement weather.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The technology is the same", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but the intent is different based on the user.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The Telephone Consumer Protection Act (TCPA) prohibits creditors from using automated dialing systems to call cell phone numbers without consent from the customer.", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7"], "text": "The TCPA\"s original purpose, protecting consumers from costly charges as a result of automated calls, has been subsumed by the new goal of preventing overly numerous call attempts to a number that (generally) is directly connected to the customer.", "type": "value", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It does not change the purpose of collection calls, ", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "it merely makes the process less efficient.", "type": "value", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["10_11", "12"], "text": "Regulating which numbers can be called using an automated dialing system is also counter to the growing reality of wireless-only households.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "According to the Center for Disease Control's 'Wireless Substitution' latest report (Early release data, July-December 2012), over one third (36%) of adults in the United States live in a household with only wireless telephone service.", "type": "fact", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "That figure is even higher (45%) when you look at children living in the US.", "type": "fact", "id": 11, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "With an average annualized growth rate of 34%, it is conceivable that sometime before 2020 only a minority of the country's adults will be living in households with a landline telephone that can be autodialed.", "type": "value", "id": 12, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The CFPB should allow for the autodialing of all telephone numbers provided by the customer without byzantine consent requirements.", "type": "policy", "id": 13, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Regardless of whether it is at application or during the course of normal business, once the number is provided by the customer to the creditor, that number should be considered another viable option for collection.", "type": "policy", "id": 14, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 234, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "They can't be sued on in court ", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and communications should reflect that.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I have found that persons who buy old debts are not competent and rely on software and letter services to fulfill their collection obligations.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "Perhaps it is time to return to licensing of collectors.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 236, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "If the present mortgage repayment debacle is any indication of noticing or added noticing I think it is much simpler to notify the consumer whom to pay and list the original creditor name.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Also, I think it would be a good idea for CFPB and the industry to combine this with FCRA issues.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "For example, if a consumer today reviews their credit reports the normal term is \"sold to another lender\" but no name.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I have heard similar stories from attorneys who try to match what a consumer lists as a creditor versus what is listed in a credit report.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2", "3"], "text": "Seems to me that everyone is trying to close the back door but leaving the front door open.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 238, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I still vividly remember receiving automated calls every Saturday morning in college insisting that I settle a debt under someone else's name.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It was a case of mistaken identity, ", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and eventually I sorted it out by tracking down the collection agency and calling them during business hours.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This was a tremendous inconvenience, however.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0_3"], "text": "I strongly support limitations on robocalls, on total call volumes, and ask that you consider creating a complaint process for harassing or mistargeted calls.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Collection agencies should face financial sanctions for misbehavior, payable to the target of their abuse.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 239, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "First, I have learned there is a significant legal difference between 1) identify theft, 2) mistaken identity (see contract law", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Furthermore, that these three words need to be separated, clarified and their legal handling completely examined.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "There is almost zero legal remedy for wrong person found.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "More information would NOT have helped.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The lawyer had plenty information ", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but he did not validate any of it after he found my address.", "type": "testimony", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The clerk told me these lawyers and their agents are \"just going through the phone book/internet\" hauling people with the same first and last name into court thinking they will eventually find the debtor.", "type": "testimony", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "A complete waste of court resources, an enormous expense to the innocent citizen, and the unlawful detainment and threatening of an innocent citizen and their assets.", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The debtor, it has since been discovered has left the county.", "type": "testimony", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The lawyer could have easily validated his information using online public property records from both the Clerk of courts and the County Clerk and found out the middle initial was not a match along with over 7 other pieces of identifying information that were not a match.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The lawyer did not even do the simplest checking.", "type": "testimony", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I filed with the IARDC ", "type": "testimony", "id": 11, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and nothing happened.", "type": "testimony", "id": 12, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 240, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["3", "4"], "text": "I had a particularly lousy experience with an abusive debt collector called Miracle Financial, working on behalf of Verizon Wireless to collect a debt I wasn't aware I had incurred and didn't believe I owed.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The full account -- and dozens more from people leaving comments on my blog over the years -- is available at the supplied link.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": ["2_4"]}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I had my identity stolen", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and I didn't even know it.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They could not produce a signed credit card receipt to compare my signature.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 302, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I would suggest a review of the language already published in the Federal Rules of Bankruptcy BR 3001( effective date 12/1/2012) relating to documentation.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Based upon my participation with the Rule and numerous comments/hearings, I believe some time can be eliminated without re-inventing a different set of standards.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Bankruptcy involves collection and involves consumers including attorneys on both sides as well.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I recommend another examination of the \"validation\" notice language and the litany of interpretations of the language.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 303, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "Debt collectors are very knowledgable in what they do.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "We are professionals.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "But debtors are not stupid and should be expected to do their own research and educate themselves to participate in their defense.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "Why should a creditor have to explain to a debtor how to avoid paying their debt.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "By the time it's reached litigation, those conversations should have already occured", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "and the debtor should be ready to offer his defense without being \"taught\" by the person to whom he owes money.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 305, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I would suggest a visit to the Federal Bankruptcy Rule 3001(effective 12/1/2012) and comments made during the proposed period, plus the hearing presentation statements published and are available.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The Rule already addresses documentation issues.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I again see that attaching all of the proposed documentation to the validation notice is not productive for the consumer or the sender.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I do believe additional documentation as to chain of title be available if a consumer is being sued in Court.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 306, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "As a creditor collecting my own debt, I assert that by the time I move to litgation, I've exhausted all other forms of collection.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I've talked to, emailed, and snail mailed the debtor.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I've tried to negotiate a payment plan or settlement offer all to no avail.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "Litigation is our last attempt.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Once we are litigation, we present our best case and let the debtor present their defense.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "My experience is that debtors don't participate in their defense out of either fear or lack of knowledge about the legal process.", "type": "testimony", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "But the burden of educating the debtor shouldn't be put on the creditor's shoulders.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["8"], "text": "If debtor's prefer to ignore the issue, then a default judgment is justified.", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "There should be consequences to the inaction of the debtor.", "type": "policy", "id": 8, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 308, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Debt collectors continuously resell the debt to other debt collectors who start the clock all over again.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Then that debt collector resells the debt ", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and the 3rd debt collector restarts the clock again, and so on.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4", "5"], "text": "The burden of proof is put on the consumer to prove it is an old debt.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The credit reporting agencies don't automatically remove old debts ", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "nor do they check to see if a newly reported debt is in fact a 9 year old debt that has been resold numerous times.", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "The credit agencies (CRA) are more of a problem for consumers than the debt collectors.", "type": "value", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The CRAs are paid by the credit card companies", "type": "fact", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and the credit card companies have bigger profits when they can charge higher rates based on poor credit scores.", "type": "fact", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7_8"], "text": "So there is inherently a huge conflict of interest here.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "If the CRAs can keep our credit scores down the card companies can make more money and don't mind paying the CRAs a piece of the action.", "type": "value", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Seems like unspoken collusion to me.", "type": "value", "id": 11, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 309, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I do not believe that it is \"just\" to allow a third party to buy a past due debt and sue for the entire balance, plus attorney fees, court costs, and other fees associated with \"mediators or arbitrators\".", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "I believe that a third party debt buyer should be limited as to how much they can sue for above their initial investment.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Too many times the original creditor is a publically traded company ", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and the loss has already been taken by the share holders.", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Then some debt buyer buys a portfolio of un-performing debt and pays a dime on a dollar for it.", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Sends all of it to a \"law office\" to collect 100% or more of the original alleged obligation.", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["8"], "text": "The debt buyer should not be able to sue for 900% of their investment.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["8"], "text": "They should be limited to a percentage of true damage.", "type": "policy", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I know of no other civil process where this would be considered ethical.", "type": "value", "id": 8, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 310, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "My company calls, auto-dials, emails, and snail mails customers many times before they are sent to a collection agency.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Many debtors simply refuse to respond to the original debtor.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They only make payment after the account is assigned to a collection agency -- akin to seeing just how far they can go before there's a consequence to not making payment.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4", "5"], "text": "Requiring a validation notice from the owner of the debt should be optional on the creditor's part.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The FDCPA requires the collection agency to send their first notice after the debt is assigned.", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7_9"], "text": "More notices from the creditor are useless and expensive.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "And the single most frequently used excuse of any debtor is \"I didn't receive the letter/invoice/statement\".", "type": "fact", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "A first class letter costs $0.55 minimum (inclusive of postage, paper, and envelope).", "type": "fact", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "That cost does not include overhead and employee cost.", "type": "fact", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Multiply that cost by the number of notices and statements already sent (and ignored) and you begin to see the true cost of collection.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 312, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "In most states all that a debt collection law office needs to provide is a complaint.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The average consumer has no idea what the difference is between a balance and a sum.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "they do not know how to calculate the interest and certainly do not know what is \"legal\" pursuant to state or Federal Credit Card Act limitations.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The name of the Plaintiff may not even be recognizable to them.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They just know that they owed some money and fell behind on bills.", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "More times than not, they do not respond at all.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 314, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "If the consumer claims identity theft then the Debt collectors should be required to prove otherwise.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The CRAs should be forbidden to report any debt that has been disputed as Identity theft unless they can provide court admissible proof that it is a valid debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The CRAs should be held more accountable and heavily fined for reporting erroneous information.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Their fines should be paid directly to the consumer for the countless hours they spend trying to fix their credit reports.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The CRAs should be required to send a letter to the consumer's insurance companies, mortgage companies, and anyone else that charged the consumer a higher rate based on their erroneous credit score and find out how much their error costs the consumer.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The sum of those added costs should be paid by the CRAs directly to the consumer in addition to the fines.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The burden of proof should fall on the CRAs and the debt collectors, not the consumer.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 315, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I have been contacted about a collection agency that stated that an old prescription charge was unpaid.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The total was like $1500.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "When I asked for proof, I received a piece of paper that had three numbers on it that added up to $1500.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Nothing more.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Literally.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0_4"], "text": "When a consumer asks for proof, they should at the very least receive a fully itemized listing of what it is is being collecting upon. (e.g. a detailed statement of account, or the un-paid invoice(s).", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Additionally, consumers should receive documentation as to why they are legally responsible. (E.g. an agreement that they signed.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["8"], "text": "I realize that for businesses that traffic in unpaid consumer debt this is going to be a huge burden ", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "as this information has long been lost.", "type": "value", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Too bad.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "At the very least, this should be the standard for any debts incurred after a certain date.", "type": "policy", "id": 10, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 318, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "Agree with RBell.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Delinquent borrowers already almost always know they're delinquent", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "so further notices are not productive.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "When notices are provided they should include the name of the original account holder and the full account number to establish a connection between any tier debt collector and the original account holder.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 320, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1", "3"], "text": "Would like to see regulators approve email as a method of delivery for notifications.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Most people keep their email even when they change physical addresses.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Harder on the post office", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but probably much more effective, with no-cost proof of attempted contact.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 321, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1_3"], "text": "Debt collectors should not be permitted to harass a debtor's ex-spouse by repeatedly calling the ex-spouse.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Debt collectors are known to use the old phone number of the debtor that now belongs to the ex-spouse exclusively.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Even though the ex-spouse tells the collector to remove her phone number from the collector's records, the collector does not,", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and then repeatedly calls her trying to get to the debtor.", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0", "5"], "text": "Collectors must be required to remove her phone number from their records at her first request and not be permitted to call her again.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Otherwise, she has no recourse to get the harassment to stop.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 324, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "Why should, an agency have to mail a letter to the consumer who requested not to be called?", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They most likely won't read it", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 325, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I don't think the consumer should have the options as to when and how they are called.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Most collection agency's today would remove a consumers phone number hen asked.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 326, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "banks can simply add this provision to their Loan Sale Agreements.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "All buyers executing a Loan Sale Agreement containing such a provision would be contractually obligated to refrain from litigating or threatening litigation.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "some current buyer would refuse to purchase with such a provision", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4"], "text": "and other current buyers would expect a price discount", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because they woudl not be able to sue.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In both instances, any inventory not acquired by current buyers would be quicly snapped up by other purchasors who would be willing to comply with these contractual provisions.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7"], "text": "Such a resolution would obviate the necessity of legislation or regulation", "type": "value", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "as the matter woudl have been taken care of under the contract between a willing seller and a willing buyer.", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "there would be no constitutional question regarding the restricting of law suits ", "type": "value", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "nor would there be any delay in implementation.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "All that would be required is the cooperation of the selling banks", "type": "value", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "which could be induced readily with some Safe-Harbor language for banks that follow this protocol.", "type": "value", "id": 11, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 327, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I think it should be illegal or miss leading for a agency to change its caller id.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "You could easily look up a relatives number and use that.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "There should be a rule regarding a change in caller id.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 331, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I don't think it matters whether a collector used a alias or not.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It's just a name. If it is used constantly", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 332, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I don't know if technology allows collectors to distinguish land lines from cell phones.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It is fair for collectors to use info provided on the application for credit.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Collectors should be allowed to assume that the mailing address of record is an accurate indication of the debtor's time zone.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Creditors periodically request updates of contact info in some cases;", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "this would be a good idea for all to do.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["6"], "text": "Mailing address should take priority for determining time zone unless the debtor advises otherwise.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "As mentioned previously, people with cell phones may move from one locale to another without changing their area code.", "type": "fact", "id": 6, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 333, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "A debt collector did not litigate a credit card debt, but summarily garnished our joint checking account.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It was two weeks later that notification was received from the debt collector.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This occurred September-October 2012.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0_2"], "text": "Debt Collectors must provide advance notice of their intent to garnish a checking account.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It took several weeks including an Order from the Judge to release the funds, only after the Debt Collector took all of a tax refund.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 334, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "In theory this seems like a reasonable policy,", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but how can collectors know where a debtor is if they are calling his or her cell phone?", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3", "4_5"], "text": "Knowingly calling third parties should be prohibited across the board.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4_5"], "text": "It is no one else's business what goes on between creditors and their debtors.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Calls to a person's boss or family can cause further financial and domestic problems,", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "neither of which will help with getting the debt paid.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 335, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "As a consumer I should receive a notice or some type of warning that the debt will be turned over to a collector.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "And when there are a change in debt collectors, the consumer should be notified.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 336, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Bank of America, my mortgage holder, does NOT even allow a formal dispute to move forward.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2_4"], "text": "The past 12 months have been a continues headache with Bank of America.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "For example, our mortgage account have always been current, and never were we in Foreclosure status, nor even approaching default.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "However, every single month Bank of America reported to the three major credit bureaus that we were late.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I've worked with their Military Liaison Officer on the resolution through phone calls, email messages, and formal letters but without success.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["6", "7"], "text": "Urgent Help/Assistance is needed for consumers to navigate and to resolve the problems that Bank of America is creating over simple and elementary issues of basic accounting procedures.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Bank of America has the undue power of making reports to the credit bureaus which adversely affects the consumer.", "type": "value", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The Consumer lacks tools to challenge and fight back on Bank of America's abuse of power.", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 337, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Debtors should be able to leave a message for a specific debtor, the name of their company and request a call-back at a specified number.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "When a consumer returns this type of call, the collector or debtor should be required to give them the mini-Miranda warning.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "There is no need for collectors to leave messages revealing the nature of their calls.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The Health Information Privacy and Portability Act prohibits disclosure of protected information to unauthorized parties", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and the same should apply to debt collectors.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 338, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "Calling a debtor at work is counter-intuitive;", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "if collectors are continuously calling someone at work, other employees may report it to the debtor's supervisor.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Most companies have established rules about receiving or making personal calls from company or cell phones during an employee's working hours.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "If a collector or creditor calls a debtor on his/her cell phone and is informed that the debtor is at work, the call should be terminated.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["5"], "text": "No calls to employers should be allowed ", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "as this jeopardizes the debtor's job.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "How does that help in debt collection? It doesn't.", "type": "value", "id": 6, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 339, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Most landlines and cell phones have caller ID technology ;", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "if the number comes up showing a toll-free number or an unknown caller, many consumers will let such calls go to voice mail.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "Voice mail messages need to be discreet.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "No one needs their kids hearing messages from debt collectors.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Anyone returning a call regarding a voice mail message should be informed by a live customer service rep of the mini Miranda warning.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This should be done only after the person returning the call to the collector verifies his or her identity as the debtor.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 340, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "Blocking caller ID information is disingenuous to say the least.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Most consumers won't respond to blocked numbers or ID's anyway.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0", "4"], "text": "Collectors should be required to identify themselves and to provide caller ID information that identifies them.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Most people who cannot pay their bills are aware of the problem,", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "so being reminded under false pretenses is more of an annoyance than a solution to the problem.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 341, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1", "2"], "text": "I'm with Massachusetts on this one.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Repetitive and robo-calls are annoying and not productive.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Another fact about robo-calls is that their messages often start in the middle,", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "or maybe this is done on purpose.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "When it has happened to me, I just hang up.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Policies regulating the number of contacts made within a specific time period should include all modes of technology.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 342, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "Consumers should not incur additional costs for cell phone calls, texting or voice messaging in relation to collections.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The more costs assessed to a debtor, the less money they have to pay their creditors.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "Debt collectors and creditors should be required to stop all modes of communication to a device that the debtor indicates does not provide free communications whether calls or texts.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 343, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I am not a lawyer,", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but I have noticed that credit card agreements often contain statements advising consumers that if suit is brought, it will occur in a specified jurisdiction or \"as provided for by law.\"", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "At the point where collectors start suing consumers is where many consumers say enough and hire a bankruptcy attorney.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The only winner in that situation is the bankruptcy attorney.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 344, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1", "3"], "text": "There should be a monetary \"floor\" required before debt collectors can pursue uncollected debts in court.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The idea that corporations that already charge puninshing interest rates and fees can clog the court systems trying to collect a few hundred bucks from someone who is unemployed, ill, or otherwise unable to pay is counter-productive.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1", "3"], "text": "There should be a minimum amount of consumer debt owed before creditors can sue debtors.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Another issue with using state and local courts to settle debt collection suits is that it burdens jurisdictions already heavily burdened with cases and strapped for cash.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 345, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Identity Theft Tops List for 13th Consecutive Year in Report of National Consumer Complaints", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": ["1"]}, {"reasons": null, "text": "http://www.ftc.gov/opa/2013/02/sentineltop.shtm", "type": "reference", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 346, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I can't comment on any of this,", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2", "3"], "text": "but it would seem appropriate for Federal law to establish a framework of requirements for states to meet.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This would level the playing field for debtors and creditors in all states.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and would provide an equal basis for states to proceed with adding or amending their own laws affecting debt collection lawsuits.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 347, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Consumers should be made aware of sale or transfer of their debts.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "From whom to whom along with effective dates and contact info for the creditor and the new owner of the debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 348, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Notifying consumers of the sale of their debts and related details would help consumers with identifying who is contacting them about a debt;", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "there are robo calls about lowering your credit card interest rate and such that are solicitations.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Consumers have a right to know who they are dealing with in relation to their financial affairs.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 349, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Consumers should be aware of who is handling collection procedures.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The seller of any consumer debt should be required to notify the debtor of which debt owed to which creditor, is being sold by xyz organization to 123 debt collector.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The effective date of the debt sale and contact info for the new collector should be included.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 350, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "A notice should go out that the debt has been sold", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "because it definitely informs the consumer in how they should go about negotiating repayment of the debt.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "When the debt is sold, it is sold for significantly less than what is owed,", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and the lender gets to write it off,", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and the borrower takes a 7-year negative hit in their credit profile.", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Sometimes when you are dealing with debt collectors, the \"debt collector\" is often a wholly-owned subsidiary of the \"original\" lender, which means they get a tax write-off; you get a hit in your credit; and they still try to collect on the entire amount.", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["5"], "text": "If a debt is sold, then it should actually be sold to a third-party, and not a subsidiary of the original lender.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["5"], "text": "And consumers should get full disclosure on who their debt has been \"sold\" to.", "type": "policy", "id": 7, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 351, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I believe the original consumer applicant on an account has the right to know if an authorized user is delinquent on her or his payments", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "as it affects the original applicant's credit standing.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "As for telling authorized card holders about the original account holder's default, I would say this is not a good idea.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Many parents provide their kids with a credit card, but would not want the credit card company contacting their kids about the parents' debt.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 352, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Consumer owing the debt should be contacted about any third party offer to pay their debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Anyone paying debt for someone else should be required to provide their identity to the creditor and debtor.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 353, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "A separate \"summary of rights\" should be sent to, and made available, to consumers.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "We are woefully uninformed and misinformed about our rights as consumers; what avenues of negotiation we can pursue; or even who can assist us.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Furthermore, there should be some laws on the books on when collectors cannot collect", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "if the original creditor has not made an attempt to collect the debt for an extended period of time, I should not get a collection notice 20 years after the fact.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 354, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "This kind of thing is likely determined by family court law in the jurisdiction where the debtor lives.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Community property law, divorce or separation agreements and issues of domestic violence laws all come into play in these kinds of circumstances.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 357, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Some people are concerned that collectors don't do much more than doublecheck that the amount in the validation notice is what the creditor says the consumer owes.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "THAT'S ALL THEY DO.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They never do anything of substance to actually push back on the creditor's claims.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": ["3"]}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I've had actual documentation that disputes creditor's claims, and all collectors do is rely on the information given them to by creditors.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["5", "6_7"], "text": "The CFPB is no better.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["6_7"], "text": "My experience with them was much the same as dealing with a collector.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7"], "text": "The CFPB did nothing to verify or investigate the creditor's claims;", "type": "testimony", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "they simply took the creditor's claims as outright facts despite conflicting documentation.", "type": "testimony", "id": 7, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 358, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1_3"], "text": "There should be a federal rule prohibiting collectors from reporting information to a CRA during the 30-day window.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "There are automated processes in place with many collectors where they will generate 4 collection letters at one time, including the one where they tell you that they have reported you to a CRA.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "And then they will mail all those to letters (all dated on the same day) to you at the same time.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "And this is done without any debt verification whatsoever.", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 359, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1_3"], "text": "Some useful documents would be the last three collection notices ACTUALLY sent to the consumer.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Too many collection agencies have claimed they sent me regular notices regarding the debt when I have not have any contact with them for 2 - 3 years.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "But they claim they have \"records\" that claim otherwise.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Yet, there is no supporting documentation of such efforts. like say, copies of the notices.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 360, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Just like mortgage servicers are required to send \"goodbye letters\" (a notification of when loan has been sold) and \"hello letters\" (a notification of when another company is buying a debt), so also should debt collectors.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Also, they should be required to disclose the amount for which they bought the debt... the discounted price.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "Also, there needs to be full disclosure as to who is buying the debt along with the disclosure of the owners of the debt collection company and the street address of the company", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "so face-to-face meetings can be arranged.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Full transparency and full disclosure should be required related to any company trying to collect debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 361, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "If I ever tell a collector that I'm recording the conversation, the call ends rather abruptly or the calls just stop.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Yet, I'm expected to be recorded whenever they initiate the call.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They expect me to have an expectation to be recorded when they want to attempt to collect a debt, ", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but the minute I want to record them while I dispute a debt, that's out of bounds...", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 362, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I should know if a debt is time-barred,", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "so that I can make an informed decision regarding the debt in question.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "The information should be in the validation notice.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "If the debt becomes time-barred after the validation notice is sent, I should be informed of the new status of the debt IMMEDIATELY!", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 363, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "If a make an offer to repay the creditor and it's refused, then the debt becomes time-barred, why should the creditor still be to sue?", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "If the creditor is offered a repayment plan, turns it down, then sues after an extended period of time, the consumer should not have to pay that debt.", "type": "policy", "id": 1, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 364, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "It has been my experience that practices can vary greatly between various creditors who find it necessary to turn delinquent or defaulted debt over to a collection agnency.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In my situation, little or no notification was given.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3", "5"], "text": "At a minimum, a creditor should give specific information as to date and which company the debt is being assigned or sold to.", "type": "policy", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Getting such a notice would help me understand that there is going to be a change with whom I would be communicating with going forward.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The costs and expenses or problems that dad honors are collectors would have been giving those is miniscule compared to the problems cause by not giving notice.", "type": "value", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4"], "text": "I would argue that they would actually save money in the long run like giving such notices.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "At a minimum, The information that should be clear that in the notice is (1) the date of when the debt would be turned over to collection agency; (2) the name address of the collection constant company to whom the doubt was assigned; and (3) specific formation about the debt collection company and a list of that company's \"best practices\", policies and procedures as to what the consumer can expect.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It would be good if there could be a single-point-of-contact for this company as well as the supervisors and owner of the collection company.", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Collection agencies need to be forced to deal more forthrightly with consumers and be required to deal with greater transparency.", "type": "policy", "id": 8, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 365, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["2"], "text": "I do not believe that it would have mattered.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It seemed that the Attorney/debt collector was not looking for the actual debtor", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "I believe that all that they were trying to do was to make a quick buck.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They did a couple of shady things with this case.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["5"], "text": "For a solution; the laws should be written so the common lay person can understand.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "If I had known that a validation request would not be considered I would not have wasted my time and paid even though it was NOT my debt.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 369, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I have personally witnessed how judges perceive credit card debt cases,", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2_3"], "text": "and I believe they have strayed too far towards the debt collectors.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Judges simply decide whether a default has occurred,", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and once a judge declares a debtor in default, the adjudicated debtor has no pleading rights.", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Alleged credit card and student loan defaulters should have the right to declare their default an Involuntary Default and be allowed to pay back the debt with no more penalties, fees or interest rate charges, called Debt Neutrality.", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Debt Neutrality is making of a debt neutral so that it does not continue to indenture a defaulter in a never ending cycle of ongoing interest rate charges, penalties and fees.", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["7"], "text": "Involuntary defaults should allow the debtor to have the debt reset to where it was at the time of the default minus any payments made.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["8"], "text": "As it stands now, Strategic Defaulters are given much better treatment than Involuntary Defaulters,", "type": "value", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "in large part due to Involuntary Defaulters not being able to plead their default as being Involuntary.", "type": "value", "id": 8, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 370, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Debt Collection companies get a very unfair debt negotiation advantage against an alleged defaulter when they hire an unscrupulous service company that has lied about giving a proper service or subservice to the alleged debtor's residence.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Judges do not seem to understand that if a service company will fraudulently state in court documents that they served a defaulter or subserved someone at the residence when in fact they did not, that the debt collector can become very arrogant and cocky as to how they negotiate with the alleged defaulter.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "In a nutshell, if the debt collector's one sided terms are not met, they will simply hire the service company who will provide service even if it is a false service.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Judges rationalize that the mail service is an adequate notification without realizing that what a false service does is embolden the debt collection company to not properly negotiate a debt with an alleged defaulter because they have total control over the service aspect, even if fraudulently obtained.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "This need to be fixed", "type": "policy", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and false servers need to be fined along with the debt collection companies who hire them and keep hiring them even after they receive complaints of false service.", "type": "policy", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 371, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1"], "text": "If I have been falsely served or subserved, (the making up of a person who does not exist to claim a service, or simply stating \"Jane Doe\" received the service) and the judges don't care, and the debt collection companies don't care, I should have the right to file an errors and omissions insurance claim against the debt collection company for false service that resulted in a verdict against me.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["2"], "text": "I have already tried asking for an errors and omissions insurance policy from the debt collection company ", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "so that I could file a claim and the debt collection company simply ignored my request.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I find this both egregious and outrageous.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 372, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I disagree with the above assessment.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "As an alleged defaulter I have asked over and over and over again to have the debt set where it was at the time of alleged default and that no more penalties fees or interest rate charges be tacked on, and that I will commit to a monthly autopay.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "People who INVOLUNTARILY defaulted because of a life changing event in their lives (such as becoming caregivers for their parents) may want to consider all of their defaults together,", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "so if five defaults occurred, the alleged defaulter has to divide whatever money they may be able to apportion every month, by five.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Debt collectors refuse to see this as a reasonable solution", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and only acknowledge their own debt with the alleged defaulter, making it impossible for the alleged defaulter to do the right thing and begin paying back everybody.", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 373, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["2", "3"], "text": "I also find the assertion that INVOLUNTARY DEFAULTERS don't put up a legal defense because they are afraid or have a lack of knowledge about the legal system to be outrageous.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Strategic Defaulters save part of the money that could have gone to pay down their debts so they can give it to an attorney who may be able to get them a sweet pay off deal.", "type": "value", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "INVOLUNTARY DEFAULTERS keep trying to make their monthly payments until the monthly accrual of interest rate charges and/or a life changing event forces then into an INVOLUNTARY DEFAULT.", "type": "fact", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "INVOLUNTARY DEFAULTS are not recognized by the courts.", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I had a SPOTLESS payment record for 15 years prior to a life changing event that caused me to become an unpaid CareGiver.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "If I could have been allowed to start with very small monthly payments to all of my creditors in exchange for having my phone lines left alone, I probably could have started making some income again.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Instead, the constant debt collection phone calls forced me to convert my land lines to 20 cent a minute cell phones that I could not even afford to answer.", "type": "testimony", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["8"], "text": "I LOST work and contacts", "type": "testimony", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["9"], "text": "because debt collectors would not accept small monthly payments as a beginning pathway towards paying off my alleged debt.", "type": "testimony", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Probably the ongoing interest rate charges on default debt makes it unrealistic for debt collectors to accept small payments.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["9"], "text": "Until alleged defaults are truly frozen so that those who want to pay them off have the best chance to do so, more and more debt will accrue.", "type": "value", "id": 10, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 375, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "Possibly the most egregious action of all regarding credit card debt occurred in 2002, suspiciously close to the 911 aftermath.", "type": "value", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "While insurance companies were paying out tens of millions of dollars to building owners who suffered damage because of 911 ", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["3"], "text": "(which technically they should not have done ", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "since this was an act of war which is NOT covered by most insurance plans), ", "type": "fact", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "the comptroller of the currency was DENYING insurance companies from competing with credit card companies in the credit card debt suspension insurance arena.", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4"], "text": "The result was a credit card debt suspension insurance monopoly for the credit card companies with premiums that were overpriced by a factor of 1000% to 2000%", "type": "fact", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The profit margin was so high for credit card debt suspension insurance that the CFPB actually had to fine the credit card companies OVER 500 MILLION DOLLARS in the summer of 2012 for overly aggressive credit card debt suspension insurance sales and marketing practices.", "type": "fact", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I had warned about overpriced credit card debt suspension insurance back in 2008 with the creation of www.credit-protector.com", "type": "testimony", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but was never compensated for my efforts.", "type": "value", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It meant that MOST credit card defaults in the United States over the last 10 to 15 years were based on a fraudulent foundation of obscenely over priced credit card debt suspension insurance that consumers could not afford to keep purchasing.", "type": "fact", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["9"], "text": "Consumers were literally paying for 5 years worth of credit card debt suspension insurance but only receiving 3-5 months worth of coverage!", "type": "fact", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Most of the times that a judge was declaring a credit card default, they were propping up the overpricing of a monopolistic credit card debt suspension insurance policy that did not fairly give consumers the most obvious way to protect themselves from a default that was caused by life changing event", "type": "value", "id": 11, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "We could literally fix the U.S. economy almost overnight by doing the right thing.", "type": "value", "id": 12, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "First acknowledge credit card debt suspension insurance fraud that the credit card companies have perpetrated on the american people over the past 10 to 15 years ", "type": "policy", "id": 13, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and as retribution reduce all consumer credit card debt by approximately 65%.", "type": "policy", "id": 14, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["16"], "text": "Then raise the monthly minimum payment on the remaining 35% from 2% to 5% ", "type": "policy", "id": 15, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "so the monthly payment remains roughly the same but consumers feel their debt more easily going forward.", "type": "value", "id": 16, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The comptroller of the currency tried to get credit card companies to raise their monthly minimum payment requirements from 2% to 4 or 5% back around 2005 but relented when it became obvious too many people would default.", "type": "fact", "id": 17, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "By reducing consumer credit card debt by 65% as a form of reparations for debt suspension insurance fraud consumers suddenly have a lot less debt BUT still have to make a similar monthly payments.", "type": "fact", "id": 18, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "However MORE of that monthly payment goes towards paying down the actual debt rather than the cesspool known as ever expanding interest rate charges.", "type": "fact", "id": 19, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 377, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I have a common last name, ", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "and for about three years I was bombarded with collection calls for other individuals with my last name and first initial.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I finally changed my phone listing from my initials to my nickname and have had only collection call since.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I am an elderly retiree.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I have no car loan or mortgage.", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I pay all my bills on time, ", "type": "testimony", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and I don't carry balances on my credit cards.", "type": "testimony", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "No debt collector has ever admitted to me that they got my number out of the phone but, ", "type": "testimony", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "but that's what they're doing.", "type": "testimony", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I would like to see every debt collector tell the individual they are calling the source of their information.", "type": "value", "id": 9, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I now have a long list of people with debts in collection.", "type": "testimony", "id": 10, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Since I'm not a debt collector,", "type": "testimony", "id": 11, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["11"], "text": "I don't believe that I have a legal obligation not to reveal their names.", "type": "value", "id": 12, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I do, however, believe that I have a moral obligation not to do so.", "type": "value", "id": 13, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Please find a way to keep debt collectors from harassing innocent people.", "type": "policy", "id": 14, "evidence": null}]}
