{"commentID": 1056, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "In order to get a default judgment through a State Court, a collector's pleadings have to spell out the theory of their case (usually contract) with sufficient specificity that a reasonable person can understand the basis for the claim.", "type": "fact", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0"], "text": "Without some form of affidavit from the actual creditor, very few courts will award a default judgment.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Also, most state court approved forms are already written for the \"least sophisticated debtor.\"", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["0", "1", "2"], "text": "I don't see any reason to impose a more stringent standard on collection lawsuits than are imposed on any other lawsuit.", "type": "value", "id": 3, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 1057, "propositions": [{"reasons": ["1", "2"], "text": "Either State or Federal law should provide some penalty for passing an NSF or \"closed account\" check that includes a presumption of guilt.", "type": "policy", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "The check either bounced or it did not.", "type": "fact", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["1"], "text": "There's not a lot of grey area here.", "type": "value", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4_5"], "text": "That said, either State or Federal law should also allow the drafter of the check a \"safe harbor\" wherein they can pay the face value of the check and some nominal compensation for the hardship suffered by the recipient of that check in order to avoid this penalty.", "type": "policy", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Michigan has such a procedure ", "type": "fact", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "and it seems relatively equitable.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}]}
{"commentID": 1059, "propositions": [{"reasons": null, "text": "I was receiving 4 or 5 calls a day from Midland Debt Collection daily for two weeks on my cellphone.", "type": "testimony", "id": 0, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "As I'm unemployed and scraping by I was ignoring - or rather trying to ignore - the calls.", "type": "testimony", "id": 1, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "They were always hang-ups.", "type": "testimony", "id": 2, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Never any message.", "type": "testimony", "id": 3, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "As I live in Indiana - a \"business-oriented\" state, ", "type": "testimony", "id": 4, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": ["4"], "text": "it seems the laws favor the debt collectors over the debtors.", "type": "value", "id": 5, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "Limits on calls? Please, do.", "type": "policy", "id": 6, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "When I finally did have the gumption to answer when they called at 8:10am on a Sunday morning, I made a strong case about being harrassed and informed him I didn't want to be contacted on my cell phone.", "type": "testimony", "id": 7, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "It's only a few days but I'll see.", "type": "testimony", "id": 8, "evidence": null}, {"reasons": null, "text": "I still don't know if it was any legit debt that they were calling about.", "type": "testimony", "id": 9, "evidence": null}]}
